# Vercel React & Next.js Performance

Reference when optimizing bundle size, refactoring, or implementing data fetching.
Source: [vercel-labs/agent-skills/react-best-practices](https://github.com/vercel-labs/agent-skills)

## CRITICAL: Eliminate Waterfalls

- Move `await` into branches where actually needed—don't block early-return paths
- Use `Promise.all()` for independent async operations
- In API routes: start promises immediately, await late; avoid sequential chains
- Use Suspense boundaries for streaming—don't block entire page for one component

```ts
// ❌ BAD: sequential
const a = await fetchA(); const b = await fetchB();
// ✅ GOOD: parallel
const [a, b] = await Promise.all([fetchA(), fetchB()]);
```

## CRITICAL: Bundle Size

- Import directly from source; avoid barrel imports (`import X from 'lib/Button'` not `import { Button } from 'lib'`)
- Use `next/dynamic` for heavy components; defer analytics/3rd-party after hydration
- Preload on hover/focus for perceived speed
- Use `optimizePackageImports` in next.config for `lucide-react`, `@mui/material`

## Server-Side

- Authenticate inside every Server Action—treat like API routes
- Use `React.cache()` for per-request deduplication; LRU cache for cross-request
- Minimize data passed to client—only serialize fields the client uses
- Parallelize RSC fetches via component composition (sibling async components)
- Avoid duplicate serialization: don't pass `users` and `users.filter(...)`; filter on client
